Of course that 2016 quarter ended up being a blip, and any investors that b=
ailed on the company paid the price in missed upside. From a structural per=
spective, it seems reasonable to think that will likely happen again: despi=
te the imminent entrance of Disney and the increased investment AT&T has pr=
omised in HBO, Netflix, by virtue of having a huge head start and huge user=
 base advantage, along with a demonstrated capability to both grow subscrib=
ers even as it increases prices, is well-placed to leverage its role as an =
Aggregator.

It=E2=80=99s been six years since then, and Netflix has weathered COVID and=
 the rise of a whole host of competing streaming services, and in the end t=
hey announced these changes in a quarter where they absolutely smashed subs=
criber projections. It=E2=80=99s good to go out on top! Still, there is rea=
son to believe that this really is the last hurrah as far as member growth =
is concerned; CFO Spencer Neumann said on the earnings call ( https://s22.q=
4cdn.com/959853165/files/doc_downloads/2024/4/netflix-inc-_earnings-call_20=
24-04-18_english.pdf ) in response to a question about future revenue growt=
h:

But when you think about the outlook for the year, it=E2=80=99s in terms of=
 the mix of revenue growth. We expect it will be pretty similar to what you=
 see in Q1, where it=E2=80=99s primarily driven by member growth because of=
 the kind of full year impact of paid sharing rolling through the year and =
continued strong acquisition and retention trends.

In other words, the Wall Street Journal had it right: the password crackdow=
n is working. The bad news is that this is a growth mechanism that is finit=
e =E2=80=94 and, to the extent that it is the biggest driver of new members=
, a reason to stop reporting them; the good news is that the fact that pass=
word sharers are in fact signing up for new plans is evidence that Netflix=
=E2=80=99s viewers think the service is worth it.

Netflix=E2=80=99s Reporting Change
--------------------------

This was Netflix=E2=80=99s explanation for the change in reporting from the=
ir shareholder letter ( https://s22.q4cdn.com/959853165/files/doc_financial=
s/2024/q1/FINAL-Q1-24-Shareholder-Letter.pdf ) :

As we=E2=80=99ve noted in previous letters, we=E2=80=99re focused on revenu=
e and operating margin as our primary financial metrics =E2=80=94 and engag=
ement (i.e. time spent) as our best proxy for customer satisfaction. In our=
 early days, when we had little revenue or profit, membership growth was a =
strong indicator of our future potential. But now we=E2=80=99re generating =
very substantial profit and free cash flow (FCF). We are also developing ne=
w revenue streams like advertising and our extra member feature, so members=
hips are just one component of our growth. In addition, as we=E2=80=99ve ev=
olved our pricing and plans from a single to multiple tiers with different =
price points depending on the country, each incremental paid membership has=
 a very different business impact. It=E2=80=99s why we stopped providing qu=
arterly paid membership guidance in 2023 and, starting next year with our Q=
1=E2=80=9925 earnings, we will stop reporting quarterly membership numbers =
and ARM.

We=E2=80=99ll continue to provide a breakout of revenue by region each quar=
ter and the F/X impact to complement our financials. For guidance, we=E2=80=
=99ll add annual revenue guidance on top of what we already provide today: =
our annual operating margin and free cash flow forecast and forecasts for q=
uarterly revenue, operating income, net income, and EPS. We=E2=80=99ll also=
 announce major subscriber milestones as we cross them.

Success in streaming starts with engagement. When people watch more, they s=
tick around longer (retention), recommend Netflix more often (acquisition) =
and place a higher value on our service. It=E2=80=99s why we=E2=80=99ve bee=
n providing progressively more information on engagement, starting with our=
 Top 10 weekly and most popular lists and more recently our bi-annual repor=
t into viewing on Netflix (which covers ~99% of all video watch time on our=
 service). This is more information than any of our competitors provide, an=
d we expect to provide even more over time.

First, I think Netflix=E2=80=99s reasoning here is by-and-large legitimate:=
 a member just doesn=E2=80=99t mean what it used to, particularly with the =
increased complexity of their offering.

Second, the majority of Netflix=E2=80=99s member growth has and will contin=
ue to come from developing markets with much lower price plans. Those membe=
rs are good to have, particularly those who mostly join to get access to Ne=
tflix content that is being produced for other markets; they=E2=80=99re jus=
t more leverage on content spending that would have happened anyways, but a=
lso aren=E2=80=99t necessarily indicative of the core health of the busines=
s.

Third, there is an argument that Netflix is in fact embracing the final bos=
s of being an Internet company by focusing on engagement as their most impo=
rtant KPI. On the Internet the only scarce resource is time and attention; =
that is what Netflix=E2=80=99s management is setting as their north star (m=
ore on this below).

All that noted, this metric was useful in measuring the progress Netflix wa=
s making in their advertising business in particular. Note this answer from=
 co-CEO Greg Peters from the earnings call in response to a question about =
the spread in pricing between the ad-supported and non-ad-supported tiers:

We don=E2=80=99t have a fixed operator position on sort of the optimal pric=
ing spread. And much like we=E2=80=99ve done with price changes in general,=
 we really use signals from our customers, things like plan take rate, conv=
ersion rates, churn to guide us along an iterative path to get to that righ=
t pricing. And I think it=E2=80=99s also probably worth noting that sort of=
 right pricing is not really a static position. As we continue to evolve an=
d improve our offering, that=E2=80=99s going to change as well. But I think=
 a good general guideline for us in the long term is that it would be healt=
hy for us to land overall monetization between our ads and non-ad offerings=
 and roughly equivalent position. So that really comes down to what works b=
est for any given member, and it=E2=80=99s really a member choice about whi=
ch plan they think serves them the best.

What Peters is saying is that the subscription price for the ad-free tier s=
hould equal the subscription price + ad revenue per user for the ad-support=
ed tier; going forward we will know the subscription prices but it=E2=80=99=
s going to be a lot more difficult to track just how well the advertising e=
fforts are going without knowing the number of subscribers (for now Netflix=
 executives admitted that the advertising tier is a drag on ARPU as the amo=
unt of inventory they have outpaces the demand from advertisers).

Netflix=E2=80=99s Waiting Game
----------------------

At one point in the earnings call, an analyst asked why Netflix was growing=
 members, above-and-beyond the password crackdown; I thought the answers pr=
ovided an amusing view into why it is that Netflix has two CEOs. Co-CEO Ted=
 Sarandos said:

That=E2=80=99s a great question. I would say the thing we=E2=80=99re doing =
is we=E2=80=99re thrilling our members. That=E2=80=99s the thing we set out=
 about why we all bounced out of bed in the morning. I look at this last qu=
arter, 8 of the first 11 weeks of the year, we=E2=80=99ve had the #1 film o=
n streaming. 9 of the first 11 weeks, we=E2=80=99ve had the #1 original ser=
ies, and I=E2=80=99m talking about hits like Avatar, The Last Airbender, Gr=
asela, Damsel, Love is Blind, [Three Body] Problem, all of that just in the=
 last few months. So this consistent and dependable and expected drumbeat o=
f hit shows, films and games, that=E2=80=99s the business that we=E2=80=99r=
e in. And that=E2=80=99s what we have to do every day, and we have to do it=
 all over the world.

Peters added:

Yes, I think that=E2=80=99s right. I mean the fundamental is all those amaz=
ing series, film, games, live events. But a key component of our something =
that we=E2=80=99re seeking to get constantly better at is that ability to f=
ind audiences for all those great titles. Part of making that happen is jus=
t the number of people who look to us for entertainment. We mentioned over =
0.5 billion people in this letter. But part of that is that product we do t=
o effectively connect those folks with titles that they will love, which th=
en enables us to find the largest audiences for those titles that we think =
that they could get anywhere. And I think as you mentioned, Ted, this appli=
es globally to titles from all over the world, which is super exciting.

In short, the content guy thinks it=E2=80=99s the content; the tech guy thi=
nks it=E2=80=99s the recommendations! I think, though, Peters=E2=80=99 poin=
t is notable, particularly given the large section of the shareholder lette=
r focused on recommendations:

At the root of strong and enduring engagement is fandom. It=E2=80=99s why o=
ur product and marketing are all designed to fuel fandom by helping members=
 discover their next obsession. Our most direct promotional tool is Netflix=
 itself, which has become the go to place for so many people looking for en=
tertainment. Our trailers, for example, generate over 6B impressions every =
month on Netflix =E2=80=94 more than 40x what they get on YouTube. Across N=
etflix, upcoming shows and movies received over 25B impressions in March al=
one, helping to build anticipation for what=E2=80=99s next. Features like =
=E2=80=9CRemind Me,=E2=80=9D which notifies members as soon as a title prem=
ieres, enable us to turn all that interest into action. And, once titles ar=
e released, we believe our personalized recommendations are much more effec=
tive at finding audiences than relying on the techniques used in traditiona=
l entertainment. It=E2=80=99s how shows like Squid Game and Lupin, or films=
 like Society of the Snow and Troll go viral =E2=80=94 reaching much bigger=
 audiences than would ever have been possible in the past.

There is one more tidbit from the earnings call (which was moderated by Net=
flix=E2=80=99s vice president of finance, corporate development, and invest=
or relations) I want to highlight, before I get to my point:

*I=E2=80=99ll now transition us to several questions around content. And th=
is first one, I=E2=80=99ll direct to Ted. It=E2=80=99s a rare question arou=
nd why don=E2=80=99t we spend more. Given what seems like a very favorable =
current backdrop for Netflix to acquire and license content, why not lean i=
n even more aggressively? Could it make sense to spend more than $17 billio=
n in cash content this year?*

Yes. Independent of the availability of licensed content, you should look a=
t it =E2=80=94 I think we=E2=80=99re =E2=80=94 we=E2=80=99ve always been ve=
ry disciplined about the way we invest in the business and how we grow it. =
And we can get a lot of bang for our buck by spending our money well and pr=
oducing our shows really well and also by acquiring the right content.
And the floodgates have opened a little more on licensing for sure. But aga=
in, we=E2=80=99re very focused on the ones that we think will drive the bus=
iness. So I think at our current level of spending and our current rate of =
growth that we=E2=80=99re pretty comfortable spending just behind that anti=
cipated rate of growth.

The long run bull case for Netflix isn=E2=80=99t just that they survive mak=
ing their own content, but rather that they move on from disrupting the cab=
le bundle to basically being the cable bundle for everything but sports (an=
d they=E2=80=99re even creeping in that direction when the money and opport=
unity makes sense). To that end, as their streaming competitors start to fa=
lter under huge losses and challenges around customer acquisition and churn=
 mitigation, it is natural to expect that Netflix might start leveraging it=
s position to start buying content from studios desperate to actually make =
money on their shows again. The company is certainly starting to do that he=
re and there, but Sarandos made clear that Netflix isn=E2=80=99t going to b=
reak its budget to seize the opportunity.

That, finally, leads to my point, and the biggest takeaway from the reporti=
ng change: I think that Netflix is well-placed to achieve that bull thesis,=
 but I get the impression the company internally realizes it has a lot of b=
uilding to do to get there. Specifically, the company came to an ad-based o=
ffering very late, and had to scramble to get it out the door, including pa=
rtnering with Microsoft. That=E2=80=99s not an optimal solution for the lon=
g run; Netflix needs to build its own platform even as it builds up its ad-=
supported user base. Meanwhile, I definitely get the impression that Peters=
 in particular thinks that the recommendation algorithm can be a lot better=
, which is another way of saying that Netflix needs to do a better job of m=
aximizing leverage on its existing content spend before it ups its budget t=
o buy more.

Basically, I get the sense that Netflix is hunkering down a bit for a slowe=
r growth consolidation phase, where it builds up the tech for recommendatio=
ns and ads (which are very much related!) in a way that will allow it to se=
rve even more content to even more people. That=E2=80=99s not necessarily a=
n approach that is going to lead to outsized subscriber growth in the short=
 term, particularly once the password sharing crackdown is over; it is some=
thing that can lead to solid profit and free cash flow numbers as long as t=
hey stay disciplined in their spending, especially if improved recommendati=
ons can drive even deeper engagement with their existing content.

I also think that Netflix can afford to wait: its competitors are seeking t=
o sell the occasional show to get cash to continue funding their streaming =
dreams; why should Netflix go out of its way to help fund those? The compan=
y can be selective with the content it acquires, improve its tech, and bide=
 its time until competing services finally give up on being streamers and a=
ccept their role as studios, on Netflix=E2=80=99s terms, and on a platform =
that is truly ready to be the only TV you need.

